<subSubSection id="C3776556EF723A16FCEFFEDDFCACFA73" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEF723A16FCEFFEDDFAABFEB3" blockId="35.[810,1452,275,2002]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FCEFFEDDFBC5FEEC" bold="true" box="[810,1024,275,301]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Material examined</emphasis>
. 
<specimenCount id="9D6BFD54EF723A16FBCEFEDDFB83FEEC" box="[1035,1094,275,301]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="female">3 ♀♀</specimenCount>
, 1 ♂ (MNHN-IU-2018-1773) and 2 dissected 
<specimenCount id="9D6BFD54EF723A16FC68FEFBFC10FE8E" box="[941,981,309,335]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">♀♀</specimenCount>
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEF723A16FBD8FEFBFA62FE91" authority="(Savigny, 1816)" baseAuthorityName="Savigny" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[1053,1447,309,336]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Herdmania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="momus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FBD8FEFBFB29FE8E" box="[1053,1260,309,335]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Herdmania momus</emphasis>
(Savigny, 1816)
</taxonomicName>
, Ibo P. 5, coral reef, 
<collectingCountry id="F37A764DEF723A16FC39FE99FB48FEB0" box="[1020,1165,343,369]" name="Mozambique" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
, 
<date id="FFD3101DEF723A16FB52FE99FAAFFEB3" box="[1175,1386,343,370]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="1995-11-10">10 November 1995</date>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEF723A16FC9AFEB7FA42FD40" blockId="35.[810,1452,275,2002]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FC9AFEB7FB18FE52" bold="true" box="[863,1245,377,403]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Diagnostic characters of female</emphasis>
. Body (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EF723A16FAFEFEB7FA61FE52" box="[1339,1444,377,403]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[136,245,1159,1185]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,192,1115]" captionTargetId="figure-353@36.[151,1436,183,1123]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Notodelphys parva Schellenberg, 1922, female. A, habitus, dorsal; B, leg 2; C, leg 5. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, C, 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591191/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 20A</figureCitation>
) dorsoventrally depressed, 1.47 mm long. Brood pouch sub-quadrate, longerthan wide. Freeurosome short, 5- segmented. Caudalramus rectangular, about 1.9 times longer than wide (125×65 μm), densely covered with transparent scales on dorsal and ventral surfaces (scales not illustrated on 
<figureCitation id="13562A58EF723A16FBC4FD8BFBAAFD9E" box="[1025,1135,581,607]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[136,245,1159,1185]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,192,1115]" captionTargetId="figure-353@36.[151,1436,183,1123]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Notodelphys parva Schellenberg, 1922, female. A, habitus, dorsal; B, leg 2; C, leg 5. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, C, 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591191/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 20A</figureCitation>
), setulose along inner and outer margins; armed with 6 setae, all located distally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEF723A16FC9AFD47FB4DFCCB" blockId="35.[810,1452,275,2002]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Antennule 15-segmented. Antenna with exopod represented by 2 subequal setae; compound distal endopodal segment extremely elongate, about 10 times longerthanwide (191×19 μm).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEF723A16FC9AFCDFFB18FB9C" blockId="35.[810,1452,275,2002]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Mandibular gnathobase with 5 teeth, second distal tooth tri- or quadricuspidate; exopod armed with 5 setae and endopod with 2 and 9 setae on first and second endopodal segments, respectively. Maxillule as usual for genus; with 10 setae on precoxal arthrite, 3 setaeon medial margin of basis, and 5 setae on unsegmented endopod. Maxilla typical for genus, with 3 setae on first endite of syncoxa and 1, 1, and 3 setae on first to third endopodal segments, respectively. Maxilliped with 9, 1, and 3 setae on first to third segments, respectively.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEF723A16FC9AFBA8FCACFA73" blockId="35.[810,1452,275,2002]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Inner distal spine of basis of leg 1 smooth and as long as first endopodal segment. Legs 2 (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EF723A16FB3CFB49FA9BFB60" box="[1273,1374,1159,1185]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[136,245,1159,1185]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,192,1115]" captionTargetId="figure-353@36.[151,1436,183,1123]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Notodelphys parva Schellenberg, 1922, female. A, habitus, dorsal; B, leg 2; C, leg 5. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, C, 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591191/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 20B</figureCitation>
) and 3 unusual in having 2 spines and 7 setae on third exopodal segment; almost all setae on these legs with defined breaking plane at proximal quarter, except outer subdistal seta. Leg 5 (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EF723A16FC0DFAC1FBF6FAE8" box="[968,1075,1295,1321]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[136,245,1159,1185]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,192,1115]" captionTargetId="figure-353@36.[151,1436,183,1123]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Notodelphys parva Schellenberg, 1922, female. A, habitus, dorsal; B, leg 2; C, leg 5. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, C, 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591191/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 20C</figureCitation>
) protopod with broad, tapering outer distal process tipped with naked seta; free exopodal segment slightly longer than wide (26×20 μm), with roundly protruded outer margin and 2 unequal, naked setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556EF723A16FC9AFA74FC9FF813" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEF723A16FC9AFA74FC31F900" blockId="35.[810,1452,275,2002]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FC9AFA74FC09FA15" bold="true" box="[863,972,1466,1492]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Remarks</emphasis>
. The presence of 2 spines and 7 setae, rather than the typical 4 spines and 5 setae as usual, on the third exopodal segment of both legs 2 and 3 is the most characteristic feature of this species. The dense ornamentation of transparent scales on the caudal rami of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEF723A16FC8FF9AAFC68F9BC" authorityName="Schellenberg" authorityYear="1922" box="[842,941,1636,1661]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Notodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FC8FF9AAFC68F9BC" box="[842,941,1636,1661]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">N. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also found in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEF723A16FBB5F9AAFABFF9BC" authority="Stock, 1967" authorityName="Stock" authorityYear="1967" box="[1136,1402,1635,1661]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Notodelphys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="steinitzi">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FBB5F9AAFB2FF9BC" box="[1136,1258,1636,1661]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">N. steinitzi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEF723A16FB36F9ADFABFF9BC" author="Stock, J. H." box="[1267,1402,1635,1661]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Sea Fisheries Research Station, Israel, 46 (Reports" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="1 - 126" part="27" refId="ref331068" refString="Stock, J. H. (1967) Report on the Notodelphyidae (Copepoda, Cyclopoida) of the Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Bulletin of the Sea Fisheries Research Station, Israel, 46 (Reports 27), 1 - 126." title="Report on the Notodelphyidae (Copepoda, Cyclopoida) of the Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Israel South Red Sea Expedition" type="journal article" year="1967">Stock, 1967</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEF723A16FCEFF94BFC01F961" author="Stock, J. H." box="[810,964,1669,1696]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Sea Fisheries Research Station, Israel, 46 (Reports" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="1 - 126" part="27" refId="ref331068" refString="Stock, J. H. (1967) Report on the Notodelphyidae (Copepoda, Cyclopoida) of the Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Bulletin of the Sea Fisheries Research Station, Israel, 46 (Reports 27), 1 - 126." title="Report on the Notodelphyidae (Copepoda, Cyclopoida) of the Israel South Red Sea Expedition. Israel South Red Sea Expedition" type="journal article" year="1967">Stock (1967)</bibRefCitation>
provided detailed comparisons between these two species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEF723A16FC9AF907FC9FF813" blockId="35.[810,1452,275,2002]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
This species was originally described from the 
<collectingRegion id="49A9F83FEF723A16FCEFF925FC98F8C4" box="[810,861,1771,1797]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Gulf" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Gulf</collectingRegion>
of Suez living in association with 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEF723A16FAE8F925FCBCF8E6" baseAuthorityName="Savigny" baseAuthorityYear="1816" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Herdmania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="momus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FAE8F925FCBCF8E6" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Herdmania momus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEF723A16FC7CF8C0FB99F8E6" baseAuthorityName="Savigny" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[953,1116,1806,1831]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Pyura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="momus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FC7CF8C0FB99F8E6" box="[953,1116,1806,1831]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Pyura momus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEF723A16FB6BF8C3FC34F888" authority="Hartmeyer, 1916" authorityName="Hartmeyer" authorityYear="1916" class="Ascidiacea" family="Styelidae" genus="Polycarpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ehrenbergi">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEF723A16FB6BF8C3FA69F8E6" box="[1198,1452,1805,1831]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Polycarpa ehrenbergi</emphasis>
Hartmeyer, 1916
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEF723A16FBCFF8E1FB37F88B" author="Schellenberg, A." box="[1034,1266,1839,1866]" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="217 - 274" part="10" refId="ref330676" refString="Schellenberg, A. (1922) Neue Notodelphyiden des Berliner und Hamburger Museums mit einer Uberscht der ascidienwohnenden Gattungen und Arten. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin, 10 (2), 217 - 274. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / mmnz. 4830100201" title="Neue Notodelphyiden des Berliner und Hamburger Museums mit einer Uberscht der ascidienwohnenden Gattungen und Arten" type="journal article" year="1922">Schellenberg, 1922</bibRefCitation>
). Subsequently, 
